title: Add generics to d3.d.ts
body:
This is a complete rewrite of d3.d.ts and is extensively breaking. By way of apology for the utterly massive pile of changes this brings in, I'm going to list what happened and why:
## Name Reorganization

Any empty namespace (things like `D3.Svg` and `D3.Geo`) have been removed, along with `D3` itself.

Type names follow the path of their associated constructor function: `d3.rgb()` returns a `d3.Rgb`, and `d3.svg.line.radial()` returns a `d3.svg.line.Radial`.
## Selections

Selections are now parameterized by their bound data. Most code should be compatible, but usage of the `.datum` method may cause some type issues. This in fact broke a test. Thanks to type unions, usage of `(d, i) => ...` can be inferred even in the object case.
## Sets

Since `d3.set` only uses string keys, it is no longer generic.
## Interpolators

Interpolation requires two values: the input value and the resulting interpolated value. This exists largely to support the interpolation of `d3.color` and its subclasses; `d3.interpolate(d3.rgb("#000"), d3.rgb("#fff"))` returns a function of `(t: number) => string`. However, there is a one-parameter variation of `d3.interpolate` that most users will find useful: `d3.interpolate("#fff", "#000")` will just work.
## Scales

Due to the interpolation issue above, scales require two parameters due to their `.interpolate` method. Constructor functions accept single-parameter variations for ease of use: `d3.scale.linear<number>()` constructs a scale whose domain and range are both numeric.
## Generators

Generators (SVG graphics, controls, and the layout functions) have zero-parameter variations that accept the D3 default types (i.e., area generators expect `Array<[number, number]>`).
## Layouts that Write to Values

Layouts like `d3.layout.tree` write values to their input. I've mimicked this with a type called `Result` which has a suite of the optional properties that are populated on a node. Input values are expected to extend this interface. Since the values are computed, they are not required on creation.
## Inheritance

D3 uses inheritance very, very sparsely. I removed any base types. They became incredibly difficult to sustain due to the way D3 changes some methods around.

The biggest offenders here are the generators and their radial equivalents. `d3.svg.line.radial()` actually creates a `d3.svg.line` under the hood, but it deletes the `x` and `y` methods, renaming them to `radius` and `angle`. It is much easier to treat the line and its radial equivalent as disparate types.
## CSV, TSV, DSV

Delimiter-separated value parsers return property bags of type `{ [key: string]: string }` instead of `any`. 
The code is parameterized over row functions, so most code will need to change uses of `d3.csv` and friends to include a row function. This is most apparent in the tests, which relied on the `any` type to pretend that the data was pre-converted.
## Overloads

D3's flexibility was extremely difficult to work with in places. I think I captured most of the spirit. However, I may have missed some edge cases. See also the `d3.extent` tests, where I had to disable some invocations because TypeScript 1.4's lib.d.ts thinks `Number.prototype.valueOf` returns an `Object` instead of a `number`.
## Other Changes

I had to rewrite `d3.layout.cloud`. It follows the pattern established by other generators, and is generic over the result interface `Word`.
## Open Issues
- The handling of `Event` is less than ideal. D3 likes to attach arbitrary properties, and it's hard to guarantee when they exist and when they don't.
- What D3 considers a "scale" varies from control to control. I ended up defining a `Scale` interface that represented what that particular control used.
- I have more than likely broken the dcjs typings. I'm not familiar with dcjs, so I was only able to make minor changes.
- I haven't added documentation comments for most of the types, functions, and modules in this library.
- There is a really strong probability that these types are overly precise.

title: Add support for dispose callbacks in knockout.projections library
body:
The Knockout Projections library has overloads for the map method which take various forms of disposal callbacks. This change adds those overloads with proper generics handling.

The computed arrays returned by map and filter both support (and practically require) disposal. Added a type which extends KncokoutSubscription to add dispose support and modified the return types of map and filter accordingly.

Updated the tests to ensure backward-compatibility with existing code.

This should address issue #3777 .

title: Add definition for D3 chargeDistance
body:
The definition for `chargeDistance` function of D3 ForceLayout is missing: [force.chargeDistance([distance])](https://github.com/mbostock/d3/wiki/Force-Layout#chargeDistance).

> #### # force.**chargeDistance**([_distance_])
> 
> If distance is specified, sets the maximum distance over which charge forces are applied. If distance is not specified, returns the current maximum charge distance, which defaults to infinity. Specifying a finite charge distance improves the performance of the force layout and produces a more localized layout; distance-limited charge forces are especially useful in conjunction with custom gravity. For an example, see Constellations of Directors and their Stars (The New York Times).

According to the Leaflet API and documentation, there were 4 missing property methods from the Leaflet.d.ts file for the L.LatLngBounds class, which have been added.

getNorth(): number
getSouth(): number
getWest(): number
getEast(): number

http://leafletjs.com/reference.html#latlngbounds

title: Upgrade nodemailer typings to 1.0
body:
The nodemailer module had a big overhaul from 0.7 to 1.0, requiring completely different typings. 

Also it is now distributed over different NPM modules 'nodemailer', 'nodemailer-smtp-transport', 'nodemailer-direct-transport' etc.  Therefore I also had to make multiple typings files and directories.

As I understand, DefinitelyTyped only hosts the newest version of typings so I replaced the 0.7 typings.
